, about the "grand contraption" we've constructed through the ages in an effort to understand and identify with the universe. According to Park, people long ago conceived of our world as a great rock slab inhabited by gods, devils, and people and crowned by stars. Thinkers imagined ether to fill the empty space, and in the comforting certainty of celestial movement they discerned numbers, and in numbers, order. Separate sections of the book tell the fascinating stories of measuring and mapping the Earth and Heavens, and later, the scientific exploration of the universe. The journey reveals many common threads stretching from ancient Mesopotamians and Greeks to peoples of today. For example, humans have tended to imagine Earth and Sky as living creatures. Not true, say science-savvy moderns. But truth isn't always the point. The point, says Park, is that Earth is indeed the fragile bubble we surmise, and we must treat it with the reverence it deserves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh  aAcademy.  aAnaximander.  aAristarchus.  aBaade, Walter, astronomer.  aBerossus.  aBoyle, Robert, chemist.  aBuddhist cosmos.  aCaligula, emperor.  aCarthage.  aCepheid variables.  aClazomenae.  aDemocritus.  aDurkheim, Emile, "ed.  aEarth Mother.  aEmpedocles.  aEratosthenes.  aEudoxus.  aGalaxy.  aGeb and Nut.  aGilgamesh.  aHenry the Navigator.  aHeracleides.  aHeraclitus.  aIonia.  aIshtar.  aJustinian.  aKepler, Johannes.  aLactantius.  aMacrobius.  aMarduk.  aMutakallimun.  aNicomachus, mathematician.  aOceanus.  aOrigen.  aParacelsus.  aanthropic argument.  aastronomical unit.  achain of being.  aconstellations.  ademon.  aeschatology.  aextinctions.  afirmament.  ainflation, theory.  amidrash.  amonotheism.  aome